data.content:
Yes! Use **ValueTuples** instead of `object[]` for type safety (MSTest 3.7+):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>` — gives you compile-time type checking and named parameters
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple syntax instead of array

Since these are simple inline values, you could also use `[DataRow]` and skip the property entirely:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

`DynamicData` with ValueTuples shines when test data involves complex types that `DataRow` can't handle (objects, collections, etc.).
